read_path_descriptions(25.10)                    read_path_descriptions(25.10)

Name
       read_path_descriptions

Syntax
       read_path_descriptions

       [-help]

       <filename>

       [-hpin]

       [-path_type   {end   summary   full   full_clock   end_slack_only  sum-
       mary_slack_only}]

       [-retime {aocv  ssta  path_slew_propagation  aocv_path_slew_propagation
       waveform_propagation}]

       Reads the file created by the write_path_descriptions command.

       This  command  reads the complete description of the paths specified in
       the file from another Tempus session and returns the data as  a  timing
       path  collection. The paths description when read back can be used as a
       regular path collection for any reporting command or queried using  the
       get_property command.

Parameters
       -help  Prints out the command usage.

       <filename>
              Specifies the name of the input file.

       -hpin  Prints all the hierarchical crossings of an arc under the "hpin"
              column in the report_timing table.

       -path_type {end | summary | full |

              full_clock  |  end_slack_only |  summary_slack_only}" Allows you
              to choose the format of the report based on the path type.

       -retime {aocv | ssta | path_slew_propagation |

              aocv_path_slew_propagation |  waveform_propagation}"  Reanalyzes
              the specified set of paths using the specified analysis method.

       Examples
              * The following example command reads out the pathfile1.txt. The
                file  contains  details of the collection of timing paths with
                hierarchical pins (-hpin) format based  on  timing  and  exact
                path availability in the session in which the path description
                is read:

                read_path_descriptions pathfile1.txt -hpin

              * The  following  command  reads in a path descriptions file and
                queries the slack:

                set read_paths_coll [read_path_descriptions path_desc.txt]

                get_property $read_paths_coll slack

                -0.123

                The following command generates a timing report from the  path
                descriptions file:

                report_timing    [read_path_descriptions    path_desc.txt]   >
                paths.rpt

